      <div id="submitting" class="generic-content-item">

        <h1>Scope & submission requirements</h1>
        <p>
          We consider submissions from all areas of academia, although our computational focus
          may result in more natural submissions from STEM fields&mdash;but all are welcome!
        </p>

        <p>
          Submissions must be "feature complete" to the extent that another educator could adopt,
          reuse, and/or extend for their purposes.
        </p>

        <p>
          The ideal submission size is a course <em>module</em>, although entire courses are also acceptable.
        </p>


        <p>JOSE submissions must:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>JOSE submissions must be fully open, under the <%= link_to "Open Definition", "http://opendefinition.org/" %>. This means that any text content or graphical objects should be under a Creative Commons license (ideally CC-BY) and code components should be under an <%= link_to "OSI-approved license", "https://opensource.org/licenses" %>.</li>
          <li>Computational learning modules should be complete and immediately usable for self-learning or adoption by other instructors. They should make a clear contribution to teaching and learning of any subject, supported by computing. JOSE is not focused in OER for "learning to code" as much as "coding to learn."</li>
          <li>Software submissions should make a clear contribution to the available open-source software that supports teaching and learning, or makes an educational process better (e.g., faster, easier, simpler). Examples include software to auto-grade student work, learning management systems, and student collaboration frameworks. Software should be feature-complete (no half-baked solutions).</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>Authors wishing to make a pre-submission enquiry should <%= link_to "open an issue", "https://github.com/#{Rails.application.settings["github"]}/issues/new?title=Pre-submission%20enquiry"%> on the <%= setting(:abbreviation) %> repository.</p>
        <div class="alert alert-primary" role="alert">
          <%= link_to "ðŸ‘€Full details about the #{setting(:abbreviation)} submission requirements and submission process&xrarr;".html_safe, "https://openjournals.readthedocs.io/en/jose/submitting.html" %>
        </div>
      </div>

